			<ns0:name>robertm@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/robertm@google.com/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Some more insights:
* the current ARM TC does not produce data bundles so at this point we are not fully committed to bkpt
* the halt instruction may be used by the linker to pad sections otherwise the service runtime is using it in various places.
* If we wanted to we could probably just standardize on one illegal instructions rather than having two around.
* I do not quite share the concerns about the possibility of the OS changing its behavior on BKPT but a PQ test would be good thing to have.
* We probably should do a little research on how other OSes handle bkpt (e.g. windows8, etc.) </ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-02-28T17:17:06.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-02-28T17:17:06.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 17 by robertm@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=446#c17" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/446/comments/full/17" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>